text:
How could I add a counter that shows the number of cards displayed with the current filtering.


To add a counter that shows the number of filtered cards, you can track the number of visible cards and display it on your page. Here's how you could do it:

1. First, add an element to your HTML where you want to display the counter, for example:
```html
<div id="card-counter">Showing 0 cards</div>
```

2. Then, modify your filtering logic to update this counter whenever the cards are filtered. Here's an example:

```javascript
function filterCards() {
    const searchInput = document.getElementById('searchInput').value.toLowerCase();
    const categorySelect = document.getElementById('categorySelect').value;
    const cards = document.querySelectorAll('.card');
    let visibleCount = 0;

    cards.forEach(card => {
        const title = card.querySelector('.card-title').textContent.toLowerCase();
        const category = card.getAttribute('data-category');
        const matchesSearch = title.includes(searchInput);
        const matchesCategory = categorySelect === 'all' || category === categorySelect;

        if (matchesSearch && matchesCategory) {
            card.style.display = '';
            visibleCount++;
        } else {
            card.style.display = 'none';
        }
    });

    // Update the counter
    document.getElementById('card-counter').textContent = `Showing ${visibleCount} cards`;
}
```

Make sure to call this filterCards function whenever your search input changes or category is selected:

```javascript
document.getElementById('searchInput').addEventListener('input', filterCards);
document.getElementById('categorySelect').addEventListener('change', filterCards);
```

This will show a count of how many cards are currently visible based on the applied filters. You can style the counter div to match your design:

```css
#card-counter {
    margin: 10px 0;
    font-size: 14px;
    color: #666;
}
```

You might want to also include the total number of cards, like this:
```javascript
const totalCards = cards.length;
document.getElementById('card-counter').textContent = 
    `Showing ${visibleCount} of ${totalCards} cards`;
```

This will give users more context about how many cards are being filtered out.
